Howdy, I am new to 3D printing but not to homebuilt CNC, which has been an interest on and off for years since I converted an X3 mill. 3D printing however will probably be a continuing interest since the setup is minimal and the materials are cheap. I have been having some bad luck with my printers however. I bought an Anycubic Kossel Linear Plus first and it started off on a good note, it produced some decent quality prints but is limited by the firmware and I believe I had some other problems with it which I have just recently resolved. Now it is printing (most of the time) like a champ.

Anycubic Kossel Linear Plus upgrades:

  • Swapped the main board with a Re-ARM + RAMPS 1.6, running Marlin 2.0 currently
  • Installed the board in my WT-LC case, and will soon be upgrading the 80mm fan on that case to a higher CFM fan.
  • Added fans and heat sinks to the X, Y and Z steppers
  • Added cooling fans to the feet
  • Replaced the plastic corners with Aluminum (one of the better upgrades I did)
  • Replaced the stepper drivers (I am going to put some TMC2130 drivers in once I get my other printer working)
  • Added TL-Smoothers

The Ender 3 (AKA "Christine" - the one from 1983), is just now starting to print well, but only after many (MANY) hours of work, and expensive upgrades including a Titan Aero, stepper heat sinks, OctoPrint and a 3d Touch probe, among other things. Seems to be worth the work though, since it is now pretty reliable. My experience with the Ender3 is not typical though, it is a really good printer for most people, I just got a bad one and my problems with it were probably compounded by a few mistakes I made along the way to fixing it.

I just purchased a (used) CR10S Pro which is an impressive printer out of the box (but needs some mechanical sett'n up like all printers). It arrived with Tinymachines firmware which I was going to put on it anyway, and I am using the Creawesome Mod for Cura which has produced some excellent test prints. The only mods I have made to the machine are:

  • Swapped the brass z-axis nuts for some anti-backlash nuts, which helped tighten things up and hopefully will resolve the problem of the z-steppers going out of sync when shutdown.
  • Upgraded the hot end to a micro-swiss (currently testing with a 0.6mm nozzle)

I'm working on a (hopefully nice looking) enclosure for the printer using mostly off the shelf parts and very little cutting (a couple straight panel cuts is what I am aiming for). When completed and tested, I will post it up with a BOM, cost estimate and links to get the parts. The project has morphed into something more complicated and I now expect to have it done around mid October (2019) if all goes well. There is a lot more printing and prototyping required for this project.

I'm happy to be a part of the great community of makers here who have shared some amazing designs. Seems that about half my stuff is re-mixed from designs others have shared, so thanks to them for that. I am hoping to contribute a bit too, and get some more designs tested and printed now that things are working better.

I use Blender to design things to print - game pieces, useful objects. It is awesome seeing what others have designed, remixed, and shared with the community. Blender is an open source project that runs on Linux/Windows/OSX, and is constantly being worked on. (I'd recommend the 3D Print Toolbox & MeasureIt plugins to make designing for 3D models easier.) If you're interested in Blender, you might check for local meetup groups...the one in Seattle (Seabug) is great! Inventimark's youtube series is a practical introduction into Blender for 3D print modeling.

If you have any questions about my models, modeling in general, printing in general, or anything from the above, I would be happy to exchange messages. (There's also a blog, where all of my learning notes go.) I'm not picky about sharing the Blender files - pre-2019 will be 2.79, 2019+ are 2.8.

I have a couple of Lulzbot Mini 1's that I've had for several years. (If you're interested, Lulzbot does offer refurbished 1.03 & 1.04 Minis on their website. Their support is awesome, and the Minis are workhorses.) The Minis come with stock .5mm nozzles, so they print faster but with slightly less detail - you can swap in Micro Swiss nozzles with 5 minutes of work. My models are usually designed for .5mm thickness, but I don't know how much that will affect you. Some of my work, I've designed for a newer nozzle (the Micro - .25, nice fan shroud).

If I don't reply to your comment here on Thingiverse, it's hard for designers to notice. We see every time someone does a like or collection with the models...and the more models we put up, the more likes/collections. If you went to the trouble of reading this profile, realize that I'm excited for feedback. If I didn't respond to a question, let me know that I missed something.

If you do sell any of my projects commercially - be good about the Creative Commons license. If they are my designs, maybe link to the project AND call me out. (CC requires attribution.) Sometimes I remix things - make sure you follow the non-commercial requirements if those have been inherited.

And finally, an appeal to design and contribute back to the community. Imagine 100 people on the site. I don't have the stats, but I'm guessing that people who give back, are probably 3-5% of the users. Even if you start by remixing models, it's a step. I'm definitely not artistic - I'm betting with a little practice, you can come up with much more creative pieces that I've done. Good luck!

We became doctors to help people and share our love of medicine. This is our way of making that dream a reality. We want to help you better understand medicine and your health.

100 years ago people got sick or injured and most of the time they knew what to do. Now we have so many different options-medications, surgeries, technology, doctors, specialists-people get overwhelmed and resort to “the doctor knows best.” While no single site can replace a medical professional and years of training, medicine should not be a foreign language. Anyone who cares about their health should have at least a basic knowledge and understanding of the language of medicine.

We are here to empower you with knowledge to not only make you a better consumer of medicine but a more well-informed and well-rounded individual.

Here’s to making you better and smarter,

Your How2Med team

bio:
My name is Ethan Reggia. I work for EIT at the University of Maryland, College Park.

Every part I design is intended to be as printer-friendly as possible, and is specifically designed for the MakerBot Replicator 2, as that is the printer I use most frequently. I generally use 0.7mm or 1.4mm thin walls, test all tolerances, and design parts to print with no raft or supports in as short a time and with as little material as possible. If you have questions or comments, please post them, and I'll do my best to reply.

My setup:
MakerBot Replicator 2 with a custom glass and aluminum build platform and an eight-slot overhead filament rack.
Glass BP washed and coated with Elmer's Disappearing Purple Washable School Glue before every print.
Standard settings unless specified otherwise (no raft or supports).
